{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"0602b1644c04963300eac1c3e09e7a70","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that both admin and customer have the same route paths for /credits and /products. I need to rename the admin routes to avoid conflicts, or the customer routes need to be adjusted. Looking at the error, it seems Next.js is treating them as parallel routes because they have the same path.\n\nThe solution is to either:\n1. Put admin routes under /admin/credits and /admin/products (which I already did), but since both have route groups, it's seeing them as conflicting.\n\nWait, the issue is that I'm using route groups (parentheses) for both admin and customer. The path would be:\n- /(admin)/credits = /credits\n- /(customer)/credits = /credits\n\nThis is the conflict. The route groups are meant to be optional but when they have the same path, Next.js doesn't know which to use.\n\nThe fix is to use different path names for admin - since I'm already using /admin prefix in the folder structure, I should keep them separate. Let me check what's happening.\n\nActually wait - I created the folders as:\n- src/app/(admin)/page.tsx -> /admin\n- src/app/(admin)/customers/page.tsx -> /admin/customers\n- src/app/(admin)/products/page.tsx -> /admin/products\n- src/app/(admin)/credits/page.tsx -> /admin/credits\n- src/app/(admin)/styles/page.tsx -> /admin/styles\n- src/app/(admin)/products/[id]/review/page.tsx -> /admin/products/[id]/review\n\nBut the customer routes are:\n- src/app/(customer)/dashboard/page.tsx -> /dashboard\n- src/app/(customer)/credits/page.tsx -> /credits\n- src/app/(customer)/products/page.tsx -> /products\n\nSo both have /credits and /products which causes the conflict.\n\nThe simplest fix is to remove the (admin) and (customer) route groups and make them actual route segments, OR rename them to avoid conflicts.\n\n\nActually, the route groups are meant to organize the code without affecting the URL. The problem is that both groups are creating the same URLs at the root level. Since the admin routes should be nested under /admin anyway, I can just remove the (admin) route group entirely and use /admin as a regular route folder instead.","signature":"78ead106b9770d2e524f9283db102b5c0557080df03102e32307ec40a43c08b5"}],"model":"MiniMax-M2.5","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":138,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":347,"cache_read_input_tokens":87870},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0fe3e04a-e649-4c3b-ad04-3a2fa78bad13","uuid":"37208825-10a2-41ed-8694-c5d2d2529154"}
